node.title: Material properties must be retrieved during material object construction to ensure correct dependency resolution
node.bodyText:
After adding the acc_slip to my ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress class and compiling successfully I get an error after submitting my script.
Below are  snippets of how I implemented the acc_slip(Accumulated slip) :
In ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress.C;
ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress::ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress(
    const InputParameters & parameters)
  : ComputeFiniteStrainElasticStress(parameters),
    _num_models(getParam<std::vector<MaterialName>>("crystal_plasticity_models").size()),
    _num_eigenstrains(getParam<std::vector<MaterialName>>("eigenstrain_names").size()),
    _base_name(isParamValid("base_name") ? getParam<std::string>("base_name") + "_" : ""),
    _elasticity_tensor(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankFourTensor>(_base_name + "elasticity_tensor")),
    _rtol(getParam<Real>("rtol")),
    _abs_tol(getParam<Real>("abs_tol")),
    _maxiter(getParam<unsigned int>("maxiter")),
    _maxiterg(getParam<unsigned int>("maxiter_state_variable")),
    _tan_mod_type(getParam<MooseEnum>("tan_mod_type").getEnum<TangentModuliType>()),
    _max_substep_iter(getParam<unsigned int>("maximum_substep_iteration")),
    _use_line_search(getParam<bool>("use_line_search")),
    _min_line_search_step_size(getParam<Real>("min_line_search_step_size")),
    _line_search_tolerance(getParam<Real>("line_search_tol")),
    _line_search_max_iterations(getParam<unsigned int>("line_search_maxiter")),
    _line_search_method(getParam<MooseEnum>("line_search_method").getEnum<LineSearchMethod>()),
    _plastic_deformation_gradient(declareProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "plastic_deformation_gradient")),
    _plastic_deformation_gradient_old(
        getMaterialPropertyOld<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "plastic_deformation_gradient")),
    _eigenstrain_deformation_gradient(
        _num_eigenstrains ? &declareProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "eigenstrain_deformation_gradient")
                          : nullptr),
    _eigenstrain_deformation_gradient_old(
        _num_eigenstrains
            ? &getMaterialPropertyOld<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "eigenstrain_deformation_gradient")
            : nullptr),
    _deformation_gradient(getMaterialProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "deformation_gradient")),
    _deformation_gradient_old(
        getMaterialPropertyOld<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "deformation_gradient")),
    _pk2(declareProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "second_piola_kirchhoff_stress")),
    _pk2_old(getMaterialPropertyOld<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "second_piola_kirchhoff_stress")),
    _total_lagrangian_strain(
        declareProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "total_lagrangian_strain")),
    _updated_rotation(declareProperty<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "updated_rotation")),
    _crysrot(getMaterialProperty<RankTwoTensor>(
        _base_name + "crysrot")), // defined in the elasticity tensor classes for crystal plasticity
    _acc_slip(declareProperty<Real>("acc_slip")),
    _print_convergence_message(getParam<bool>("print_state_variable_convergence_error_messages"))
{
  _convergence_failed = false;
}

void
ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress::initQpStatefulProperties()  
{
  _plastic_deformation_gradient[_qp].zero();
  _plastic_deformation_gradient[_qp].addIa(1.0);



  if (_num_eigenstrains)
  {
    (*_eigenstrain_deformation_gradient)[_qp].zero();
    (*_eigenstrain_deformation_gradient)[_qp].addIa(1.0);
  }
  else
  {
    // set to identity if no eigenstrain is added
    _inverse_eigenstrain_deformation_grad.zero();
    _inverse_eigenstrain_deformation_grad.addIa(1.0);
  }

  _pk2[_qp].zero();
  
  _total_lagrangian_strain[_qp].zero();

  _updated_rotation[_qp].zero();
  _updated_rotation[_qp].addIa(1.0);

  for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _num_models; ++i)
  {
    _models[i]->setQp(_qp);
    _models[i]->initQpStatefulProperties();
  }

  for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _num_eigenstrains; ++i)
  {
    _eigenstrains[i]->setQp(_qp);
    _eigenstrains[i]->initQpStatefulProperties();
  }
  
   _acc_slip[_qp] = 0.0;


}

void ComputeMultipleCrystalPlasticityStress::computeQpStress() 
{
  for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _num_models; ++i) {
    _models[i]->setQp(_qp);
    _models[i]->setMaterialVectorSize();
  }
  for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _num_eigenstrains; ++i)
    _eigenstrains[i]->setQp(_qp);

  updateStress(_stress[_qp], _Jacobian_mult[_qp]);

   // Update _acc_slip
    for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _num_models; ++i)
  {
    const MaterialProperty<std::vector<Real>>& slip_increment_property = getMaterialProperty<std::vector<Real>>("slip_increment");

    const std::vector<Real>& slip_increment = slip_increment_property[_qp];
      
     
    for (const auto& value : slip_increment)
    {
      _acc_slip[_qp] += value; // Accumulate slip increments from all models for the current quadrature point
    }
  }
}

node.title: Nodal boundary conditions via imported CSV
node.bodyText:
Hi guys,
I've been looking at Nodal boundary conditions, unfortunately I couldn't find it any where on MOOSE source page.
So the idea would be this, I have a csv table of nodes and their DirichletBC value, not sure how should I implement this into MOOSE.

As far as I can see, most of the MOOSE BCs require 'boundary', but I don't want this, I don't want to define any surface.

1
My initial idea would be this: import CSV file via PropertyReadFile but the problem with this method would be that I would have to prepare the CSV file with all the nodes in the domain (rather than just the nodes at boundary/surface) + I don't want to impose any value outside the boundary/surface even with 0 value
then use PiecewiseConstantFromCSV to store the value from PropertyReadFile > then use FunctionDirichletBC to impose the BC values, but again FunctionDirichletBC requires boundary name/ID
2
Another more silly approach would be that I generate 100 of thousand boundaries using SideSetsFromPointsGenerator or pre-generate it elsewhere, and assign DirichletBC to each one of them (can be done via an action too).
3
Another method would be to create my own Nodal boundary conditions.
If you have any idea or have implemented this, please let me know.
Thank you!
Kind regards,
Traiwit
I see that there are NodalBC.C and NodalBCBase.C in the source files, which might be useful, I will investigate further

Hello
I think 1 would work out of the box.
Note that you can specify bogus values for all the nodes that you dont care about in the CSV file. The only values that will be used by a FunctionDirichletBC would be the nodes on the boundary. It doesnt query anywhere else, the values would be ignored.
2 will not help you with your memory issues
3 would be the cleaner one, calling the propertyReadFile directly from the BC object. As you prefer though.
Guillaume
Hello, have you found a way to add node boundary conditions?

Hi,
yes, you need to use PropertyReadFile > PiecewiseConstantFromCSV > FunctionDirichletBC

[UserObjects]
  [uobj_pwp_read_AllNodes]
    type = PropertyReadFile
    prop_file_name = 'pwp_atALLNODES_rhoGdZminus10m.csv'
    nprop = 2
    read_type = node

[]

[]

[]

node.title: Do TIMESTEP_BEGIN and TIMESTEP_END make sense for t=0?
node.bodyText:
Check these boxes if you have followed the posting rules.

 Q&A General is the most appropriate section for my question
 I have consulted the posting Guidelines on the Discussions front page
 I have searched the Discussions forum and my question has not been asked before
 I have searched the MOOSE website and the documentation does not answer my question
 I have formatted my post following the posting guidelines (screenshots as a last resort, triple back quotes around pasted text)

Question
I want to do a transient simulation of a set of beams. In order to verify that I set up the simulation correctly, I wanted to recover the expected resonance frequencies known from analytical solutions. To this end, I initialized 'disp_y' as given by the respective mode. For example, the initial position of the end of the beam, i.e. at 'x=10', has the initial value '-1'. This seems to work fine so far.
I also had to modify 'computeProperties' in ComputeIncrementalBeamStrain.C, since it wouldn't compute an incremental strain otherwise, but that shouldn't matter for my question.
Consider the four ways to log information about the displacement of the end of the beam:
 [disp_y_1]
   type = PointValue
   point = '10 0.0 0.0'
   variable = disp_y
   execute_on = "TIMESTEP_BEGIN"
 []
 [disp_y_2]
   type = PointValue
   point = '10 0.0 0.0'
   variable = disp_y
   execute_on = "TIMESTEP_END"
 []
 [disp_y_3]
   type = PointValue
   point = '10 0.0 0.0'
   variable = disp_y
   execute_on = "INITIAL TIMESTEP_BEGIN"
 []
[disp_y_4]
   type = PointValue
   point = '10 0.0 0.0'
   variable = disp_y
   execute_on = "INITIAL TIMESTEP_END"
 []

They only differ in how 'execute_on' is set. Below you can see the results for the first several timesteps:
t: [0.   0.01 0.02 0.03]
disp_y_1: [ 0.         -0.99999923 -0.81280427 -0.2029271 ]
disp_y_2: [ 0.         -0.81280427 -0.2029271   0.53472652]
disp_y_3: [-0.99999923 -0.99999923 -0.81280427 -0.2029271 ]
disp_y_4: [-0.99999923 -0.81280427 -0.2029271   0.53472652]

When I don't use 'INITIAL' in 'execute_on', the logged values are just zero. So my question is: What does it even mean TIMESTEP_BEGIN and TIMESTEP_END for t=0? How does it work under the hood?
Many thanks and best regards,
Felix

Hello
INITIAL is an execution step that is right after the initialization of variables, and the solver has not run yet.
TIMESTEP_BEGIN is before the solver runs, and TIMESTEP_END after, as the solution is not the end-of-timestep solution
Both options makes sense, though timestep_end will not be at t=0 in your case, it will be at t=0.01
You can use the Debug/show_execution_order=ALWAYS to see the progression of the execution steps
@GiudGiud thank you for your response! I think I didn't fully understand it yet. Let me ask you instead: In what case does it make sense to use TIMESTEP_END or TIMESTEP_BEGIN for t==0?

It makes sense to use timestep begin if you are starting from t = 0 and want to output the initial solution. And same for the next time steps, you want the solution at the time which is at the beginning of the time step
If you want the solution after the nonlinear solve, at the end of the time step (the beginning of the next one in a way, but objects may execute in between), then timestep_end is more appropriate

Thank you very much again. I understand the second part you wrote, I think. The first part I don't.

Keep in mind, INITIAL is before time step begin. So many people use "INITIAL TIMESTEP_END" for the execute_on of any postprocessing (both the PPs and the outputs)

Question
Hello
I need to insert the diffusion term value (Div.Grad v)/|Grad v| in the derivativeparsedmaterial. Here is my approach:
I crearted a kernel that calculates (Div.Grad v)/|Grad v| where v is the coupled variable and the kernel variable is defined as curr.
Now I am using curr as a coupled_variable in the DerivativeParsedmaterial to evaluate the material.
Couple of questions:
Is this the right approach?  I tried using only material to calculate the (Div.Grad v)/|Grad v|. However, I could not find the way to resolve the divergence part as there is no test function.
I also tried using auxvariable but was not able to do this.
Thanks

Hello

I crearted a kernel that calculates (Div.Grad v)/|Grad v| where v is the coupled variable and the kernel variable is defined as curr.

do you mean an auxiliary kernel (auxkernel)? Kernels compute contributions to the residual, only auxkernels can set variable values

However, I could not find the way to resolve the divergence part as there is no test function.

why do you need the test function?

why do you need the test function?

Div.Grad v is there that means double differentiation. So, I was thinking if I can write this as auxkernel  as
return - (_grad_test[_i][_qp] * _grad_v[_qp])/_grad_v[_qp].norm();
However, as computeQpResidual() does not work for auxkernel like the kernel system. I was wondering if there was some way out.
Otherwise how to get double differentiation in auxkernel.
_gradient(coupledGradient("gradient_variable")) only differentiates once. Please provide the syntax to get a double differential
Thanks

coupledSecond gets you the double derivatives
in the Coupleable interface (coupleable.h), same as coupledGradient
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/interfaces/Coupleable.html

what finite element fammily are you using?
anything first order has a second derivative of 0
you'll need to go higher order, (or code a multi-element stencil, difficult) to get non-zero second derivatives
